I am not sure what the kid is up to but it is not on the level.  He states he is wanting to trade for a 1911 and willing to put up cash with his XDS. Save your time and skip this one guys, no need to get jerked around.

title: For Sale:  .308 / 7.62x51 NATO
postcontent:
Up for sale: 1,000 rounds of 7.62x51mm training ammo made in Germany. These rounds have a plastic case and bullet and are non-corrosive. These are used for training by the German Army and Special Forces - but you can use them where ever (within reason of course :)

These are a ton of fun to use - virtually no recoil, much quieter than the full-power ammo and much lighter. I have shot 1,000's of these rounds of the past several years and they are awesome! I got rid of my .308 rifle, so now I don't have a use for them. I personally used this ammo for sighting in new scopes, target practice, small game hunting, plinking, etc. I have taken out ground hogs, rabbits, squirrels, etc. at well over 150 yrds with this stuff, no problem. This ammo will easily shoot right through 3/4" plywood at 150 yrds.

One of the many things I like about this ammo is you can shoot much more of it than traditional ammo, and faster, without heating up/warping your barrel or breaking your wallet. Not to mention, it produces very little carbon or other metallic build ups like traditional ammo does. You can shoot 100's of rounds and cleaning is a breeze. As far as accuracy goes, the manufacture claim is this stuff is accurate past 200 yrds. I have tested up to 150 yrds and can confirm it is very accurate at that distance. Perfect for teaching young or new shooters. That being said - THESE ARE BULLETS THAT CAN KILL JUST THE SAME AS METAL BULLETS. These are not a toy and need to be used in a responsible manner. According to the manufacture, this ammo reaches speeds of 4300+ FPS. Again, this is not a toy and CAN KILL!!!

Note: I have only ever used this ammo in a bolt action rifle, not sure how it would act in a semi-auto.

Here is a YouTube video of this exact same ammo. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DnEdwZv9WsU

The case I have is factory sealed, never opened. I would like to keep it that way but would entertain breaking it up. Price for the 1,000 round case is $300 OBO. This is less than a 3rd of what traditional 308/762.51 ammo is going for. Using this ammo in place of traditional ammo even a third of the time will same you lots of money.
